goals.question: What is the overall trend of unemployment across industries?

goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the industries that have been most affected by unemployment over time.

goals.question: Which industry has the highest unemployment rate?

goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the industry that has the highest unemployment rate and can be used to focus on the factors that contribute to this trend.

goals.question: What is the relationship between education level and unemployment rate?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot showing the relationship between education level and unemployment rate
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the relationship between education level and unemployment rate and can be used to determine the impact of education on employment opportunities.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment rate across industries?
goals.visualization: Histogram showing the distribution of unemployment rate across industries
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the industries that have a high or low unemployment rate and can be used to determine the factors that contribute to this trend.

goals.question: What is the average unemployment rate across industries?
goals.visualization: Box plot showing the distribution of unemployment rate across industries
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the average unemployment rate across industries and can be used to compare the industries and determine the factors that contribute to the differences in unemployment rate.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='date', y='unemployment_rate', hue='industry', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of unemployment across industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.legend(title='Industry', loc='upper left')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.barplot(x='industry', y='unemployment_rate', data=data)
    max_unemployment_rate = data['unemployment_rate'].max()
    plt.axhline(y=max_unemployment_rate, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Highest Unemployment Rate: {max_unemployment_rate:.2f}')
    plt.title('Which industry has the highest unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Industry')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='unemployment_rate', hue='industry', multiple='stack', palette='tab10', legend=True)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployment rate across industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.legend(title='Industry', loc='upper right')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    ax = sns.boxplot(x='industry', y='unemployment_rate', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the average unemployment rate across industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Industry')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.legend(title='Industries', loc='upper right', labels=data['industry'].unique())
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
